post_text:
Dear Parent or Guardian,
The deadline to apply for P-EBT food benefits has been extended to July 31. Please review the criteria to see if your family is eligible and needs to apply for benefits. Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT) is a one-time benefit for eligible families to buy food. Immigration status does not matter when applying for P-EBT. The public charge rule does not apply to P-EBT benefits.

P-EBT is for children 5-18 years old who received SNAP food benefits for the month of March 2020. P-EBT is also for children up to 21 years old who are certified for free or reduced-price meals through the National School Lunch Program at school during the 2019-20 school year. Children that attend a school that offers free meals to all students (Community Eligibility Provision or Provision 2) are also eligible.
• Fill out an application here: https://yourtexasbenefits.com/Learn/PEBT (the URL is case-sensitive)

post_text: The Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer, or P-EBT, application is open. You should have received a school email or letter with more information on how to apply for these food benefits. P-EBT is for children who received SNAP food benefits for March 2020 and for children who are certified for free or reduced-price school meals during the 2019-20 Texas school year. You could receive up to $285 per child on a P-EBT card to purchase food at stores. If you have not received P-EBT information from your school, please contact 833-613-6220. Visit hhs.texas.gov/PEBT for more information.

post_text: Our last senior to be recognized from the OHS Class of 2020 is Charles Malina. Charles actually graduated early in December, but we definitely wanted to recognize him with his class. Charles is an extremely intelligent young man. He has made so many contributions to OHS through his efforts and successes in UIL Academics, UIL CX Debate, and UIL One Act Play. He was also an athlete and FFA member. Charles has the potential to be a great leader and contributor to society in the future! Even though he has already begun his higher education journey, we wish him continued blessings and success!

post_text: Our second senior to be recognized this week is Kara Miller. Kara is the daughter of Suzanna Leathers. Kara has been an active member of UIL OAP, UIL Academics, FFA, FCA, Beta Club, Yearbook Stuff, and the Panther Theater Group. Kara is a great student and will graduate with 27 college credit hours and is the Class Historian of the Class of 2020. Your intelligence and talent (and wit) will take you far in life! Good luck to you in your future endeavors!

post_text: Our second senior to be recognized this week is Neci Keefer. Neci is the daughter of John and Lacy Keefer. She is also an excellent student and will graduate with 30 college credit hours. She's also been involved in FFA, FCA, and UIL. Neci plans to attend Blinn College in the fall and pursue a career in nursing. Neci appears to be quiet but she has a great and funny personality once you get to know her. She has a bright future ahead of her and we can't wait to see where life takes her!

Key is an athlete at heart and what a joy it has been for all of us at OHS to follow him throughout the years. Of note, he is the two-time back to back state Champion in the triple jump and we feel certain that had all of this not happened, he would have been a three-time champion. Key is a great student and a great welder according to Mr. Brown. He has a great deal of potential and we wish him well in the future! We love you Key! (Also, please be sure to read the faculty comment page)

We appreciate your patience and support as we try to take care of all of our kids.

post_text:
Review the criteria for exemptions for grades 7-12.

If you have a 75-79 no absences.

If you have 80-89, 1 absence

If you have 90-94, 2 absences

If you have 95 or higher, 3 absences.

■All absences, except medical, court, school sponsored trips or a college visit, count against the student for exemption purposes. Medical means a Dr.’s appointment and you are at school part of that day. If you are gone the entire day that is not considered medical.
■Students can elect to take the test to raise their grade
■Exemptions can be revoked up to the day of the test
■Students who are failing the class will not be eligible for exemptions
■Three tardies in any one class equals an unexcused absence for that class.
■Students in grades 7/8 will be allowed to choose which 2 core subjects that wish to apply the exemption to each semester. They will be required to take the other 2 core exams. All students who meet the exemption criteria will be allowed to exempt elective courses.

Exemptions can change all the way up to the day of the exam.

■All absences, except medical, court, school sponsored trips or a college visit, count against the student for exemption purposes. Medical means a Dr.’s appointment and you are at school part of that day. If you are gone the entire day that is not considered medical.
■Students can elect to take the test to raise their grade
■Exemptions can be revoked up to the day of the test
■Students who are failing the class will not be eligible for exemptions
■Three tardies in any one class equals an unexcused absence for that class.
■Students in grades 7/8 will be allowed to choose which 2 core subjects that wish to apply the exemption to each semester. They will be required to take the other 2 core exams. All students who meet the exemption criteria will be allowed to exempt elective courses.

Exemptions can change all the way up to the day of the exam.

Yesterday, OISD had the privilege of presenting the very first Johnson Foundation Project Award to Oakwood 6th grade student, Nick Strickland. The Johnson Foundation Project was started by Oakwood alumni Dominic Johnson. We are so proud of Nick and so very proud of Dominic and the change he is creating in the world. Please see the statement from Dominic below:

"Please excuse my absence. However, I am excited about the official birth of the Johnson Foundation Project. It gives me great pleasure to present this award on behalf of my late father's birthday. Now with that being said, I've started my very own non-profit organization that serves to highlight and reward students that have gone above and beyond in their studies, sports, etc. These students are the type that are never afraid of failure, but only hungry for success."
